00:37:33.240 --> 00:37:35.400
And then also, a
lot of the stuff

00:37:35.400 --> 00:37:37.440
that's revealed in that
book, I haven't read it.

00:37:37.440 --> 00:37:40.090
She's like, every
night turning over,

00:37:40.090 --> 00:37:42.550
like, did you know--
one of these things.

00:37:42.550 --> 00:37:45.040
I mean, the amount of
drinking Nixon was doing.

00:37:45.040 --> 00:37:47.931
Those types of facts-- I'm
curious, where you aware

00:37:47.931 --> 00:37:48.430
of that?

00:37:48.430 --> 00:37:49.940
And then just in
general, where else

00:37:49.940 --> 00:37:52.310
did you take research
from around some

00:37:52.310 --> 00:37:54.282
of the real meaty
historical stuff?

00:37:54.282 --> 00:37:56.490
AUSTIN GROSSMAN: The more
facts you read about Nixon,

00:37:56.490 --> 00:37:58.550
the more you realize
that he didn't

00:37:58.550 --> 00:38:00.720
have any of the
political discipline

00:38:00.720 --> 00:38:03.690
that a contemporary
president has.

00:38:03.690 --> 00:38:05.320
Yes, he drank like crazy.

00:38:05.320 --> 00:38:09.095
He would drink and
make crazy phone calls.

00:38:13.860 --> 00:38:17.140
If a modern President tried
to do the things he did,

00:38:17.140 --> 00:38:20.630
he would have five advisors who
would tackle him to stop him.

00:38:20.630 --> 00:38:24.970
I mean, the example
is after Kent State,

00:38:24.970 --> 00:38:30.690
all these protesters are lined
up on the Lincoln Memorial.

00:38:30.690 --> 00:38:32.300
Hippy kids are
just camped there.

00:38:32.300 --> 00:38:35.270
And Nixon drinks until 4:00 am.

00:38:35.270 --> 00:38:38.770
And then he goes out in person
onto the Lincoln Memorial

00:38:38.770 --> 00:38:39.760
to talk to them.

00:38:39.760 --> 00:38:41.970
Like, he just walks
across the lawn.

00:38:44.570 --> 00:38:48.780
Can you imagine a contemporary
President just drunkenly

00:38:48.780 --> 00:38:51.230
mingling with the
protesters and nobody--

00:38:51.230 --> 00:38:54.170
they would hit him with a
tranquilizer dart or something.

00:38:54.170 --> 00:38:55.935
They would just stop it.

00:38:58.860 --> 00:39:01.520
At least he was--
there are moments

00:39:01.520 --> 00:39:04.960
when you can detect
a human being who

00:39:04.960 --> 00:39:07.930
is just willing to fuck up.

00:39:07.930 --> 00:39:11.460
And again, it's a
little sad that we've

00:39:11.460 --> 00:39:14.890
lost that, I have to say.

00:39:14.890 --> 00:39:17.560
Anyway, it's weirdly
the summer of Nixon.

00:39:17.560 --> 00:39:21.440
There were, like, two or
three books that came out,

00:39:21.440 --> 00:39:22.880
not even counting mine.

00:39:22.880 --> 00:39:24.590
And I'm not sure
why that is, other

00:39:24.590 --> 00:39:27.852
than people who
were born with Nixon

00:39:27.852 --> 00:39:29.268
are old enough to
write books now.

00:39:29.268 --> 00:39:31.290
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:31.290 --> 00:39:32.540
AUSTIN GROSSMAN: There you go.

00:39:32.540 --> 00:39:33.415
Someone did research.

00:39:33.415 --> 00:39:36.900
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
after Reagan and Hinckley,

00:39:36.900 --> 00:39:37.400
[INAUDIBLE].

00:39:46.809 --> 00:39:48.350
AUSTIN GROSSMAN:
That's a good point.

00:39:48.350 --> 00:39:50.310
It's a weird sea change
when Reagan came in,

00:39:50.310 --> 00:39:51.890
the more you look at it.

00:39:51.890 --> 00:39:55.200
Anyway, the book I read for this
was called "Nixon Agonistes"

00:39:55.200 --> 00:39:56.030
by Gary Wills.

00:39:56.030 --> 00:39:57.740
And it's a terrible
title, but I really

00:39:57.740 --> 00:40:00.350
think it's one of the
most brilliant piece

00:40:00.350 --> 00:40:03.160
of political journalism
I have ever seen.

00:40:03.160 --> 00:40:06.790
There's a great scene where
he's on the plane with Nixon

00:40:06.790 --> 00:40:07.850
as he's campaigning.

00:40:07.850 --> 00:40:11.910
And he talks to Nixon,
but everyone's sleeping

00:40:11.910 --> 00:40:13.410
so the lights are kind of out.

00:40:13.410 --> 00:40:15.440
And he talks to Nixon
and he's talking

00:40:15.440 --> 00:40:16.860
and he can't see Nixon's face.

00:40:16.860 --> 00:40:18.568
And suddenly, he
realized when you're not

00:40:18.568 --> 00:40:21.610
staring at Nixon's face, he
becomes a totally different

00:40:21.610 --> 00:40:28.065
person, because the hypnotic
jowls and nose armature just

00:40:28.065 --> 00:40:29.190
turns him into a character.

00:40:29.190 --> 00:40:30.648
But when you can't
see his face, it

00:40:30.648 --> 00:40:32.267
feels more like
talking to a person.

00:40:32.267 --> 00:40:33.350
Anyway, it's a great book.

00:40:33.350 --> 00:40:34.390
It may be out of print.

00:40:34.390 --> 00:40:35.230
I'm not sure.

00:40:35.230 --> 00:40:38.194
I had to special order it.

00:40:38.194 --> 00:40:39.860
I did a bunch of
research, but I'm never

00:40:39.860 --> 00:40:45.737
going to be the guy who
has the-- I did what

00:40:45.737 --> 00:40:47.320
felt like the right
amount of research

00:40:47.320 --> 00:40:49.570
so that I could then start
making stuff up from there.

00:40:49.570 --> 00:40:51.730
I'll put it that way.

00:40:51.730 --> 00:40:53.160
Every once in a
while, I deviated

00:40:53.160 --> 00:40:55.329
from the historical
record here and there.

00:40:55.329 --> 00:40:57.370
The night of Watergate,
Nixon was in the Bahamas,

00:40:57.370 --> 00:40:58.480
or his body double was.

00:40:58.480 --> 00:41:00.170
We don't know.

00:41:00.170 --> 00:41:02.729
And then I actually
transferred some

00:41:02.729 --> 00:41:04.770
of the rides between Disney
World and Disneyland.

00:41:04.770 --> 00:41:06.686
And actually, the biggest
pushback I've gotten

00:41:06.686 --> 00:41:11.130
is messing with some of
the details of Disney World

00:41:11.130 --> 00:41:12.270
versus Disneyland.

00:41:12.270 --> 00:41:14.290
Make of that what you will.

00:41:14.290 --> 00:41:15.790
Did you know that
in the early '60s,

00:41:15.790 --> 00:41:17.920
they wouldn't let
Khrushchev into Disneyland?

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:20.660
He wanted to go, and they
were like, no, no, you can't.

00:41:20.660 --> 00:41:23.672
What were they hiding?

00:41:23.672 --> 00:41:26.200
AUDIENCE: So in the book,
some of the presidents

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:27.820
know about the
supernatural activities

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:29.980
and some of the other
presidents have no idea,

00:41:29.980 --> 00:41:31.460
or they only suspect.

00:41:31.460 --> 00:41:34.035
How did you decide which
presidents would be in the know

00:41:34.035 --> 00:41:35.410
and which ones
would be ignorant?

00:41:35.410 --> 00:41:37.800
AUSTIN GROSSMAN: Well,
it came out weird.

00:41:37.800 --> 00:41:41.570
The idea is that at the founding
of the Plymouth colonists

00:41:41.570 --> 00:41:49.800
and then the founding of
the proper United States

00:41:49.800 --> 00:41:53.550
becomes a sort of magical
pact with the native elder

00:41:53.550 --> 00:42:00.520
spirits of the
continental United States.

00:42:00.520 --> 00:42:02.920
And that certain powers
and responsibilities

00:42:02.920 --> 00:42:07.250
devolve onto the president as
a kind of intrinsic element

00:42:07.250 --> 00:42:08.090
to that contract.

00:42:08.090 --> 00:42:09.670
But that knowledge is lost.

00:42:09.670 --> 00:42:11.870
It's lost during the
Civil War and then

00:42:11.870 --> 00:42:14.440
Taft kind of
semi-reconstructs it.

00:42:14.440 --> 00:42:16.840
But part of what
happens to Nixon

00:42:16.840 --> 00:42:20.580
is Eisenhower knows the
most about it of anybody

00:42:20.580 --> 00:42:21.580
during the 20th century.

00:42:21.580 --> 00:42:24.000
But in '57, Eisenhower
has a stroke.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.050
And in the book, he
loses the knowledge.

00:42:26.050 --> 00:42:29.030
So Nixon was supposed to be
briefed on what a sorcerer

00:42:29.030 --> 00:42:29.870
president does.

00:42:29.870 --> 00:42:31.150
But then he doesn't know.

00:42:31.150 --> 00:42:33.350
He's left adrift.

00:42:33.350 --> 00:42:37.260
It works out for some reason
that nearly all the presidents

00:42:37.260 --> 00:42:38.870
in the know are Republicans.

00:42:38.870 --> 00:42:41.350
And it was not on purpose.

00:42:41.350 --> 00:42:46.130
It just worked out that way
that the Republican lineage

00:42:46.130 --> 00:42:50.820
makes it the dominant
one, although I

00:42:50.820 --> 00:42:53.730
will say it's not the
ideological Republicans

00:42:53.730 --> 00:42:54.590
of today.

00:42:54.590 --> 00:42:57.580
Eisenhower was--
and Nixon himself

00:42:57.580 --> 00:43:02.905
was virtually completely
distinct of the Reagan

00:43:02.905 --> 00:43:09.560
and post-Reagan Republican
to the point where he's

00:43:09.560 --> 00:43:11.890
more or less unrecognizable.

00:43:11.890 --> 00:43:14.040
But yes, it just ended
up being the Republicans

00:43:14.040 --> 00:43:16.590
because-- it ended up being
passed down within one party

00:43:16.590 --> 00:43:18.960
and that ended up
being the Republicans.

